text: #apstats Countdown Tip 2: Skim read through all the FRQ. See a question you feel confident about? Do it first. Make notes as you go to remember what you were thinking when you return to finish the problem you got stuck on.

text: #apstats Countdown Tip 3: When attacking a MC question, look at the answer choices.  How are they alike? What makes them different?  Without doing too much work, can you eliminate some of the answers.

text: #apstats Countdown Tip 4: Write clearly and concisely. Be careful with the words “it” and “they”. Will the person reading your test know what you are talking about?

text: #apstats Countdown Tip 5: When you write a regression equation, be sure to define your variables and put a hat on the response variable. Your equation is technically a statistic based on a sample of bivariate data from a population.

text: #apstats Countdown Tip 6: Deciding on paired t-test or 2 sample t-test?  Does it make sense to pair the data and look at the mean of the differences? (Yes = paired-t) Was it based on 2 independent random samples? (Yes = 2 sample t-test)

text: #apstats Countdown Tip 7: Don’t forget context in your conclusion for your hypothesis test. Example: reject Ho-we have enough evidence to conclude the mean capacity of the soda cans is less than 12 ounces.
